103
00:04:36,583 --> 00:04:43,148
it's how we as humans, as a species, deal with time.

104
00:04:43,148 --> 00:04:45,730
So stories themselves are these structured

105
00:04:45,730 --> 00:04:47,471
reliances of experiences.

106
00:04:47,471 --> 00:04:50,093
And we normally think of things like movies and books,

107
00:04:50,093 --> 00:04:51,355
but just look around us.

108
00:04:51,355 --> 00:04:53,857
We have SportsCenter.

109
00:04:53,857 --> 00:04:56,419
We have the same kind of thing I was just talking about,

110
00:04:56,419 --> 00:04:59,561
but for athletic events, we have history.

111
00:04:59,561 --> 00:04:59,621
So.

112
00:05:02,290 --> 00:05:04,751
It's a cool idea, but how does that help us?

113
00:05:04,751 --> 00:05:11,712
So, the main thing that this lets us do is three things.

114
00:05:11,712 --> 00:05:15,093
Interesting moments, share the same anatomy,

115
00:05:15,093 --> 00:05:17,573
so we're able to analyze any type of thing

116
00:05:17,573 --> 00:05:20,654
that's not traditionally story using the same frameworks

117
00:05:20,654 --> 00:05:21,534
and kind of push them around.

118
00:05:21,534 --> 00:05:23,214
For games, this is really essential

119
00:05:23,214 --> 00:05:27,075
because we're so multimedia, we're so all over the place

120
00:05:27,075 --> 00:05:28,475
in terms of the ways that we engage players

121
00:05:28,475 --> 00:05:30,216
and the ways that we push things towards them.

122
00:05:31,552 --> 00:05:33,152
It also centers the player's experience.

123
00:05:33,152 --> 00:05:36,514
Again, we're not talking about what my goal was,

124
00:05:36,514 --> 00:05:39,516
what the team's goal was, what the meta commentary is.

125
00:05:39,516 --> 00:05:42,598
It's entirely focused on the individual or the group

126
00:05:42,598 --> 00:05:47,761
that is experiencing your story, your medium, your content.

127
00:05:47,761 --> 00:05:50,702
They're the center of it, and it lets us focus on that.

128
00:05:50,702 --> 00:05:53,844
And the third thing is this benefits immensely

129
00:05:53,844 --> 00:05:55,045
from iteration.

130
00:05:55,045 --> 00:05:58,167
Like, stories themselves are these kind of

131
00:05:58,167 --> 00:06:00,908
whittling down affairs when you're making them.

132
00:06:00,908 --> 00:06:01,248
And...

133
00:06:02,675 --> 00:06:05,496
You know, it's how we got to make things like Last of Us

134
00:06:05,496 --> 00:06:06,316
as good as they are.

135
00:06:06,316 --> 00:06:08,977
Just trying and trying again, layering and layering again.

136
00:06:08,977 --> 00:06:11,757
So really quickly, let's kind of break down

137
00:06:11,757 --> 00:06:13,578
what I mean by all of that.

138
00:06:13,578 --> 00:06:15,898
All interesting moments share an anatomy.

139
00:06:15,898 --> 00:06:17,279
So I actually did a talk on this

140
00:06:17,279 --> 00:06:19,159
a little more thoroughly yesterday.

141
00:06:19,159 --> 00:06:20,139
You guys can check it out on the vault.

142
00:06:20,139 --> 00:06:23,420
But the basic way I like to look at it

143
00:06:23,420 --> 00:06:26,441
is using this methodology called Kishoten Kets.

144
00:06:26,441 --> 00:06:28,581
Gonna go really fast through this.

145
00:06:28,581 --> 00:06:30,982
You basically have a setup, you have a development,

146
00:06:30,982 --> 00:06:32,082
you have a twist.

147
00:06:32,352 --> 00:06:33,073
and you have a payoff.

148
00:06:33,073 --> 00:06:34,214
This is how jokes work.

149
00:06:34,214 --> 00:06:36,315
This is how most story beats work.

150
00:06:36,315 --> 00:06:38,137
Again, how a football game can even work.

151
00:06:38,137 --> 00:06:42,220
It's just a analysis of what makes things interesting.

152
00:06:42,220 --> 00:06:44,481
You set expectations, you twist them,

153
00:06:44,481 --> 00:06:46,103
and then you pay off the consequences.

154
00:06:46,103 --> 00:06:49,365
The Mario games use this quite a bit right now.

155
00:06:49,365 --> 00:06:51,327
Mark Brown has done an amazing video

156
00:06:51,327 --> 00:06:54,970
just breaking down key shot tenkets for about 15 minutes.

157
00:06:54,970 --> 00:06:59,213
We're not gonna cover that here, but really recommend it.

158
00:06:59,213 --> 00:07:00,794
And yeah, centers the player's experience.

159
00:07:02,018 --> 00:07:03,740
They're the center of this universe.

160
00:07:03,740 --> 00:07:06,722
Everything we do is to affect their subjective

161
00:07:06,722 --> 00:07:10,726
moment to moment experience in this.

162
00:07:10,726 --> 00:07:13,168
Benefits from direct iteration.

163
00:07:13,168 --> 00:07:14,049
Story is writing.

164
00:07:14,049 --> 00:07:16,611
