00:11:40,409 --> 00:11:40,790
and that...

264
00:11:43,179 --> 00:11:44,720
Joel is still lying to her.

265
00:11:44,720 --> 00:11:46,581
She doesn't know about what,

266
00:11:46,581 --> 00:11:49,282
but she knows he's hiding something.

267
00:11:49,282 --> 00:11:54,925
And this then leads to their unraveling.

268
00:11:54,925 --> 00:11:57,206
So yeah, pretty straightforward.

269
00:11:57,206 --> 00:11:58,966
Just a recap of the story,

270
00:11:58,966 --> 00:12:03,068
but hopefully you can see how we kind of stack these

271
00:12:03,068 --> 00:12:04,769
on top of each other to create that rhythm,

272
00:12:04,769 --> 00:12:05,529
to create that pulse,

273
00:12:05,529 --> 00:12:09,511
to accomplish everything we tried to do and deliver it.

274
00:12:09,511 --> 00:12:12,152
It's delicious, it's great.

275
00:12:12,152 --> 00:12:12,873
Good storytelling.

276
00:12:13,404 --> 00:12:15,785
Nothing crazy.

277
00:12:15,785 --> 00:12:16,746
That's cool.

278
00:12:16,746 --> 00:12:20,948
But how did we actually find and develop these moments?

279
00:12:20,948 --> 00:12:23,029
Like, I just gave you a list.

280
00:12:23,029 --> 00:12:25,410
I didn't tell you how I got there.

281
00:12:25,410 --> 00:12:27,691
So let's go into that.

282
00:12:27,691 --> 00:12:28,872
Track three, characters.

283
00:12:28,872 --> 00:12:32,493
The main thing to understand

284
00:12:32,493 --> 00:12:34,894
about our style of storytelling at Naughty Dog,

285
00:12:34,894 --> 00:12:36,075
and mine personally,

286
00:12:36,075 --> 00:12:37,596
is we try to work from this premise

287
00:12:37,596 --> 00:12:40,697
that characters drive the story's beats.

288
00:12:40,697 --> 00:12:41,898
Everything we just described

289
00:12:42,183 --> 00:12:45,745
was due to an action of these characters.

290
00:12:45,745 --> 00:12:47,926
Joel is the one giving the surprise.

291
00:12:47,926 --> 00:12:49,166
Ellie is the one reacting.

292
00:12:49,166 --> 00:12:50,987
Ellie pushes forward into the annex.

293
00:12:50,987 --> 00:12:54,048
All of these things, it's pretty basic,

294
00:12:54,048 --> 00:12:57,189
but they're driven by what these characters want

295
00:12:57,189 --> 00:12:58,450
and who they are.

296
00:12:58,450 --> 00:13:02,211
So we understand that characters drive the story's beats,

297
00:13:02,211 --> 00:13:03,512
but what drives them?

298
00:13:03,512 --> 00:13:06,153
We need to understand the people coming along with us

299
00:13:06,153 --> 00:13:08,834
into the story.

300
00:13:08,834 --> 00:13:10,394
And how do we do that?

301
00:13:10,394 --> 00:13:10,915
Break it down.

302
00:13:12,130 --> 00:13:14,411
First, we do things like look at their character history.

303
00:13:14,411 --> 00:13:17,371
Who are they and what have they been through?

304
00:13:17,371 --> 00:13:19,352
This is Ellie and Joel.

305
00:13:19,352 --> 00:13:24,613
They have been through an entire The Last of Us together.

306
00:13:24,613 --> 00:13:29,014
All of that, their trauma, their grief,

307
00:13:29,014 --> 00:13:30,754
got resolved in the end of that.

308
00:13:30,754 --> 00:13:33,955
They are thinking that they are living

309
00:13:33,955 --> 00:13:34,995
their happily ever after.

310
00:13:34,995 --> 00:13:40,016
Game's done, Ellie was saved, no cure,

311
00:13:40,016 --> 00:13:40,856
bit of a loss, but.

312
00:13:41,450 --> 00:13:43,350
They're trying to move forward.

313
00:13:43,350 --> 00:13:44,511
They're both looking to the future.

314
00:13:44,511 --> 00:13:47,992
Since we understand these contexts,

315
00:13:47,992 --> 00:13:49,132
and this covers everything else with them,

316
00:13:49,132 --> 00:13:50,693
their personality, their history,

317
00:13:50,693 --> 00:13:54,194
Joel's from Austin, Ellie's grew up mostly in Boston,

318
00:13:54,194 --> 00:13:56,255
different vibes, but the main thing

319
00:13:56,255 --> 00:13:57,815
that this character history gives us

320
00:13:57,815 --> 00:14:00,916
is it helps us understand what these characters want.

321
00:14:00,916 --> 00:14:03,737
And then we are able to take those wants

322
00:14:03,737 --> 00:14:05,298
and drive them into actions.

323
00:14:05,298 --> 00:14:06,118
So, quick breakdown.

324
00:14:06,870 --> 00:14:09,732
Joel's main want in this scene, in this flashback,

325
00:14:09,732 --> 00:14:11,194
is he wants to live the life he had

326
00:14:11,194 --> 00:14:13,095
before he lost Sarah with Ellie.

327
00:14:13,095 --> 00:14:13,976
And he's getting to do that.

328
00:14:13,976 --> 00:14:15,477
He's a dad again.

329
00:14:15,477 --> 00:14:19,201
He's got the daughter, shaped hole in his heart, filled.

330
00:14:19,201 --> 00:14:22,544
Ellie wants to see the world progress again.

331
00:14:22,544 --> 00:14:28,389
She grew up really, really harshly,

332
00:14:28,389 --> 00:14:31,171
and now has experienced what she sees

333
00:14:31,171 --> 00:14:32,312
as the only bit of stability.

334
00:14:33,575 --> 00:14:35,537
She's very much on the pro like,

335
00:14:35,537 --> 00:14:37,138
oh hey, the world can actually be good though.

336
00:14:37,138 --> 00:14:41,041
Imagine that.

337
00:14:41,041 --> 00:14:42,482
And you know, her love of space and science,

338
00:14:42,482 --> 00:14:44,043
always looking ahead, kind of reflect this.

339
00:14:44,043 --> 00:14:45,785
But then we take the next layer,

340
00:14:45,785 --> 00:14:48,567
which is this is what these people want on the surface.

341
00:14:48,567 --> 00:14:50,568
This is their most primary drive.

342
00:14:50,568 --> 00:14:55,212
But they also have secret wants.

343
00:14:55,212 --> 00:14:58,114
Joel's pretty simple.

344
00:14:58,358 --> 00:15:00,399
wants to keep hiding the truth about the fireflies.

345
00:15:00,399 --> 00:15:02,720
That man does not want anybody to know what he did.

346
00:15:02,720 --> 00:15:06,160
Does not want Ellie to know what he did.

347
00:15:06,160 --> 00:15:08,941
Ellie still secretly wants to know what happened.

348
00:15:08,941 --> 00:15:13,522
You know, they have these two aligning superficial goals

349
00:15:13,522 --> 00:15:16,483
that let them bond, let them really

350
00:15:16,483 --> 00:15:17,843
just become a family unit,

351
00:15:17,843 --> 00:15:20,924
but that core tension underneath

352
00:15:20,924 --> 00:15:23,345
that we get to tug out at the end

353
00:15:23,345 --> 00:15:24,265
shows how they unravel.

354
00:15:24,265 --> 00:15:27,486
How they go from there to here.

355
00:15:28,959 --> 00:15:30,379
So yeah, the secret wants come forward,

356
00:15:30,379 --> 00:15:32,481
unravel both of them, Joel starts to lose Ellie.

357
00:15:32,481 --> 00:15:35,342
Ellie fears she misses her chance to matter.

358
00:15:35,342 --> 00:15:37,103
She's starting to kind of question and worry.

359
00:15:37,103 --> 00:15:39,545
It's like, wait, what part was he lying about?

360
00:15:39,545 --> 00:15:44,527
And yeah, the best way to think about this too

361
00:15:44,527 --> 00:15:46,969
is that story isn't picking words.

362
00:15:46,969 --> 00:15:51,591
It's finding the actions that bring characters to life.

363
00:15:51,591 --> 00:15:52,652
So how do we go about doing that?

364
00:15:52,652 --> 00:15:55,433
We're not trying to sit down necessarily

365
00:15:55,433 --> 00:15:57,875
and type out a script or just bunker up.

366
00:15:58,355 --> 00:15:59,776
One of the things that I really liked

367
00:15:59,776 --> 00:16:00,957
with our process at Naughty Dog

368
00:16:00,957 --> 00:16:05,019
is it was very kind of focused on acting in improv.

369
00:16:05,019 --> 00:16:08,200
So we would just brainstorm, feel it out,

370
00:16:08,200 --> 00:16:10,501
play as the characters, use all of this knowledge

371
00:16:10,501 --> 00:16:12,883
and history to just come up with dumb moments.

372
00:16:12,883 --> 00:16:16,044
Like it turns out, a lot of Naughty Dog is ex-theater kids.

373
00:16:16,044 --> 00:16:19,446
And if you were to just like pop into the office,

374
00:16:19,446 --> 00:16:20,867
somebody would probably be rolling on the ground,

375
00:16:20,867 --> 00:16:22,247
other people would be using voices,

376
00:16:22,247 --> 00:16:24,188
they'd be having fake shouting arguments,

377
00:16:24,188 --> 00:16:26,329
but you know, can't really show that here.

378
00:16:28,883 --> 00:16:31,865
But yeah, it honestly though, like that approach

379
00:16:31,865 --> 00:16:34,506
is what I think got us some of these

380
00:16:34,506 --> 00:16:35,847
like very lively feeling moments.

381
00:16:35,847 --> 00:16:37,568
We didn't pre-plan a script,

382
00:16:37,568 --> 00:16:40,069
we just worked from the characters,

383
00:16:40,069 --> 00:16:42,031
tried to actually imagine what they would do

384
00:16:42,031 --> 00:16:43,631
in these situations.

385
00:16:43,631 --> 00:16:46,353
So yeah, if you guys want some more resources on characters

386
00:16:46,353 --> 00:16:48,154
and how we kind of built all of this out,

387
00:16:48,154 --> 00:16:50,895
we've got the Art of Dramatic Writing by Lagross Angry,

388
00:16:50,895 --> 00:16:53,317
Creating Character Arcs by K.M. Weiland,

389
00:16:53,317 --> 00:16:55,278
and of course, Robert McKee's story.

390
00:16:55,278 --> 00:16:55,558
So that's cool.

391
00:16:59,082 --> 00:17:03,263
But what about the player?

392
00:17:03,263 --> 00:17:04,123
Let's talk about gameplay.

393
00:17:04,123 --> 00:17:08,524
So I've mostly just talked about what happens,

394
00:17:08,524 --> 00:17:10,205
who these characters are.

395
00:17:10,205 --> 00:17:12,985
This is a game, there's a player,

396
00:17:12,985 --> 00:17:15,546
there's somebody that is in the room with us

397
00:17:15,546 --> 00:17:18,847
that isn't there until the game ships.

398
00:17:18,847 --> 00:17:20,667
So how do we bring them into this experience?

399
00:17:20,667 --> 00:17:24,988
How do we involve them in this thing that we're doing?

400
00:17:24,988 --> 00:17:26,428
This is acting, this is improv.

401
00:17:27,350 --> 00:17:31,490
Simplest way that I've been able to articulate this

402
00:17:31,490 --> 00:17:34,251
is we approached it as if the player is an actor

403
00:17:34,251 --> 00:17:34,751
that we cast as Ellie.

404
00:17:34,751 --> 00:17:39,172
That means that this person, this performer,

405
00:17:39,172 --> 00:17:41,892
collaborating with Ashley Johnson basically,

406
00:17:41,892 --> 00:17:44,353
has the agency to drive her actions.

407
00:17:44,353 --> 00:17:46,313
They might not be able to branch

408
00:17:46,313 --> 00:17:48,173
and decide what those actions are,

409
00:17:48,173 --> 00:17:49,434
they're still the impulse.

410
00:17:49,434 --> 00:17:51,054
They are still the one doing this.

411
00:17:51,054 --> 00:17:53,194
They are acting from a script basically.

412
00:17:53,194 --> 00:17:54,074
That's how acting works.

413
00:17:54,074 --> 00:17:55,475
You don't go on stage and

414
00:17:56,322 --> 00:18:01,866
do a choose your own adventure play, you do your part.

415
00:18:01,866 --> 00:18:02,907
They are the impulse.

416
00:18:02,907 --> 00:18:06,810
They get to decide though still, some decisions,

417
00:18:06,810 --> 00:18:09,372
the timing and the tone of those decisions.

418
00:18:09,372 --> 00:18:12,374
They get to decide the what, the when, the why,

419
00:18:12,374 --> 00:18:16,457
and it takes us to the next part.

420
00:18:16,457 --> 00:18:19,019
We also want to ensure that these decisions,

421
00:18:19,019 --> 00:18:21,421
these choices we're giving the player,

422
00:18:21,421 --> 00:18:22,882
provide emotional expression.

423
00:18:22,882 --> 00:18:24,963
They are either letting them,

424
00:18:25,743 --> 00:18:29,566
facilitate or express an emotion that they think Ellie should have.

425
00:18:29,566 --> 00:18:35,110
So they also get to let her explore her different reactions.

426
00:18:35,110 --> 00:18:38,393
So I can press a button going like, oh, I wonder what Ellie's going to do with this,

427
00:18:38,393 --> 00:18:42,396
and then get surprised, get this feedback that it's like, oh, she's going to make a

428
00:18:42,396 --> 00:18:43,156
stupid joke.

429
00:18:43,156 --> 00:18:45,318
She's going to get on Joel's nerves.

430
00:18:45,318 --> 00:18:46,199
I want to see that.

431
00:18:46,199 --> 00:18:47,320
I align myself with that.

432
00:18:47,320 --> 00:18:52,444
I'm exploring this character interactively in a way that, you know, it's not quite acting,

433
00:18:52,444 --> 00:18:53,885
but it's, I think, something.

434
00:18:54,659 --> 00:18:55,960
enriching nonetheless.

435
00:18:55,960 --> 00:18:58,560
And then the final part is feedback.

436
00:18:58,560 --> 00:19:01,401
So we have agency, expression,

437
00:19:01,401 --> 00:19:02,862
but the next part is yes-anding,

438
00:19:02,862 --> 00:19:05,603
is like taking what the player's trying to do

439
00:19:05,603 --> 00:19:06,683
and saying, oh, that's cool.

440
00:19:06,683 --> 00:19:09,864
Also, developing it, throwing it back.

441
00:19:09,864 --> 00:19:12,285
Again, kind of going back to this improv framework

442
00:19:12,285 --> 00:19:12,985
that we're working from.

443
00:19:12,985 --> 00:19:15,746
It also then drives the next expression.

444
00:19:15,746 --> 00:19:17,307
It drives the next decision for the player.

445
00:19:17,307 --> 00:19:19,248
You're actually having a back and forth

446
00:19:19,248 --> 00:19:21,848
instead of, I don't know, filling out a spreadsheet

447
00:19:21,848 --> 00:19:23,489
or going on a hike.

448
00:19:25,456 --> 00:19:27,999
And some examples of this that we can kind of cover are,

449
00:19:27,999 --> 00:19:31,142
you are the real person to press the button

450
00:19:31,142 --> 00:19:32,303
to shove Joel into the water.

451
00:19:32,303 --> 00:19:33,364
It isn't a cut scene.

452
00:19:33,364 --> 00:19:36,066
It's not perfectly timed or canned.

453
00:19:36,066 --> 00:19:37,748
It's whatever you feel like it.

454
00:19:37,748 --> 00:19:39,349
Whenever you, honestly, as the player,

455
00:19:39,349 --> 00:19:43,192
I think he's expecting it the least.

456
00:19:43,192 --> 00:19:46,295
That way you get that bit of extra satisfaction.

457
00:19:46,295 --> 00:19:49,458
Same thing with the swimming.

458
00:19:50,330 --> 00:19:53,110
Really simple, but just this exploration of a new mechanic.

459
00:19:53,110 --> 00:19:54,991
Up until this point, you've not been able to swim

460
00:19:54,991 --> 00:19:57,011
in this game, we're at about like eight hours in,

461
00:19:57,011 --> 00:20:00,752
you get a new expressive way to navigate the environment,

462
00:20:00,752 --> 00:20:02,212
learning things like diving underwater.

463
00:20:02,212 --> 00:20:05,433
You can also find some secret stuff,

464
00:20:05,433 --> 00:20:06,613
like climbing on the dinosaur,

465
00:20:06,613 --> 00:20:10,194
just being this reckless kid,

466
00:20:10,194 --> 00:20:11,754
clambering up the nearest cool thing

467
00:20:11,754 --> 00:20:13,595
that she finds when she's excited,

468
00:20:13,595 --> 00:20:16,495
and getting to, again, like emotionally express that,

469
00:20:16,495 --> 00:20:19,316
getting to just align with the performance

470
00:20:20,289 --> 00:20:21,590
She's just jazzed to be there.

471
00:20:21,590 --> 00:20:22,511
She's actually also kind of happy

472
00:20:22,511 --> 00:20:25,654
that she's screwing with Joel.

473
00:20:25,654 --> 00:20:29,116
Or her finding a hat, messing around,

474
00:20:29,116 --> 00:20:31,879
going into the back rooms, cracking jokes.

475
00:20:31,879 --> 00:20:32,719
These are all optional.

476
00:20:32,719 --> 00:20:35,962
These aren't essential to her performance,

477
00:20:35,962 --> 00:20:37,984
but they're things that you as a player

478
00:20:37,984 --> 00:20:39,945
get to own having added to the performance.

479
00:20:39,945 --> 00:20:41,787
You're the one who has decided that,

480
00:20:41,787 --> 00:20:43,228
like, yeah, this is Ellie.

481
00:20:43,228 --> 00:20:44,609
This is who she is.

482
00:20:44,609 --> 00:20:47,031
You're collaborating with us.

483
00:20:47,031 --> 00:20:49,073
You're adding to the scene

484
00:20:49,073 --> 00:20:49,513
rather than just...

485
00:20:50,942 --> 00:20:53,683
doing it by rote.

486
00:20:53,683 --> 00:20:55,664
And yeah, that's just how we approached

487
00:20:55,664 --> 00:20:57,325
a lot of these small sections,

488
00:20:57,325 --> 00:20:59,646
putting hats on the dinosaurs, putting the hats on Joel,

489
00:20:59,646 --> 00:21:01,187
even going back to emotional expression,

490
00:21:01,187 --> 00:21:03,688
literally letting you just go into a mirror

491
00:21:03,688 --> 00:21:04,989
and make stupid faces.

492
00:21:04,989 --> 00:21:09,091
Can't get any more direct than that.

493
00:21:09,091 --> 00:21:12,392
Choosing your hats, deciding how long you want to examine

494
00:21:12,392 --> 00:21:13,833
this gift that Joel's given you,

495
00:21:13,833 --> 00:21:17,875
you're the one to jump off, move forward.

496
00:21:17,875 --> 00:21:19,636
And then when things start taking a turn.

497
00:21:20,753 --> 00:21:22,234
There's nothing at all in the game

498
00:21:22,234 --> 00:21:24,736
asking you to turn on your flashlight or crouch,

499
00:21:24,736 --> 00:21:26,917
pretend that it's, you know, you're in danger.

500
00:21:26,917 --> 00:21:29,638
You're the one doing that as the player.

501
00:21:29,638 --> 00:21:31,659
You're embodying these emotions.

502
00:21:31,659 --> 00:21:34,221
By this point, we've gotten you so deep in

503
00:21:34,221 --> 00:21:36,942
that you're not really consciously doing this,

504
00:21:36,942 --> 00:21:39,344
but all the same, you're providing the performance.

505
00:21:39,344 --> 00:21:43,026
You're providing the emotional alignment

506
00:21:43,026 --> 00:21:44,326
that Ellie is then acting out in the game.

507
00:21:44,326 --> 00:21:45,827
So yeah, that's how we approach this gameplay.

508
00:21:51,601 --> 00:21:52,862
The player is an actor cast as Ellie.

509
00:21:52,862 --> 00:21:55,943
If you want more resources on this,

510
00:21:55,943 --> 00:21:57,824
I would recommend Directing Actors by Judas Wetson,

511
00:21:57,824 --> 00:22:02,167
Manga and Theory in Practice by Hirohiko Araki,

512
00:22:02,167 --> 00:22:03,768
and of course, Story by Robert McKee.

513
00:22:03,768 --> 00:22:06,409
I told you they'd be back.

514
00:22:06,409 --> 00:22:08,891
But again, that's cool.

515
00:22:08,891 --> 00:22:12,393
But how does the player know all of this?

516
00:22:13,167 --> 00:22:14,728
We have all this elaborate plan for them.

517
00:22:14,728 --> 00:22:18,190
We've tried to convince them to be an actor

518
00:22:18,190 --> 00:22:20,112
in our weird digital stage play,

519
00:22:20,112 --> 00:22:21,793
but we didn't send them a script.

520
00:22:21,793 --> 00:22:25,735
We didn't let them know that this was going on.

521
00:22:25,735 --> 00:22:28,737
How does this work?

522
00:22:28,737 --> 00:22:34,161
The simple answer is level design.

523
00:22:34,161 --> 00:22:36,642
So the way we try to use level design in this scene

524
00:22:36,642 --> 00:22:39,624
is that space informs the player of direction and mood.

525
00:22:40,697 --> 00:22:42,438
It lets them perform without that script.

