this is the template for a lot of what I pursue

785
00:33:57,758 --> 00:33:58,778
as a creative.

786
00:33:58,778 --> 00:34:02,401
This is the template that I'm like striving for now

787
00:34:02,401 --> 00:34:03,342
after seeing this.

788
00:34:03,342 --> 00:34:06,344
Like it changed the trajectory of my creative ambitions.

789
00:34:06,344 --> 00:34:07,464
It was just that important to me.

790
00:34:07,464 --> 00:34:10,106
But enough about that.

791
00:34:10,106 --> 00:34:14,049
Let's get into the next stage, which is production.

792
00:34:14,049 --> 00:34:16,190
The how do.

793
00:34:16,190 --> 00:34:21,914
How do we actually take all of these compositional things

794
00:34:22,342 --> 00:34:24,303
and make it happen.

795
00:34:24,303 --> 00:34:26,163
So let's take a quick look.

796
00:34:26,163 --> 00:34:29,544
So we had teams and timelines.

797
00:34:29,544 --> 00:34:33,586
My role on this project officially was level design.

798
00:34:33,586 --> 00:34:35,546
Basically, I was the first designer on the ground,

799
00:34:35,546 --> 00:34:37,507
I created the layouts, some of the prototypes,

800
00:34:37,507 --> 00:34:39,327
and then coordinated the teams at each stage.

801
00:34:39,327 --> 00:34:41,268
I was basically the person who, quote unquote,

802
00:34:41,268 --> 00:34:42,268
owned the level.

803
00:34:42,268 --> 00:34:43,589
Doesn't mean I did everything

804
00:34:43,589 --> 00:34:45,169
or was the main person in charge.

805
00:34:45,169 --> 00:34:46,329
I was just the person responsible

806
00:34:46,329 --> 00:34:47,970
for making sure everybody was talking to each other.

807
00:34:47,970 --> 00:34:50,831
So at the start, it was just me.

808
00:34:51,462 --> 00:34:53,043
The way we just generally do it is like,

809
00:34:53,043 --> 00:34:54,925
we start with a level designer and a lead

810
00:34:54,925 --> 00:34:56,906
kind of working together to incubate it.

811
00:34:56,906 --> 00:34:58,227
We move it up to a four person strike team

812
00:34:58,227 --> 00:35:01,029
until it's kind of cooking a little bit better.

813
00:35:01,029 --> 00:35:02,670
And then as we move into alpha and play testing,

814
00:35:02,670 --> 00:35:04,872
we slowly ramp up to more and more people,

815
00:35:04,872 --> 00:35:07,314
more and more people, until at full production,

816
00:35:07,314 --> 00:35:08,194
it's all hands on deck.

817
00:35:08,194 --> 00:35:09,796
The maximum amount of people working on it,

818
00:35:09,796 --> 00:35:10,856
all departments are involved,

819
00:35:10,856 --> 00:35:13,598
everything is just firing in all cylinders.

820
00:35:13,598 --> 00:35:17,521
Also, I didn't work on this level beginning to end

821
00:35:17,521 --> 00:35:18,382
in one big chunk.

822
00:35:19,869 --> 00:35:22,110
Each of us had about three to five levels

823
00:35:22,110 --> 00:35:24,450
that we accomplished and wove together

824
00:35:24,450 --> 00:35:25,531
for over about two years.

825
00:35:25,531 --> 00:35:28,052
So I wanna talk about this process a little bit.

826
00:35:28,052 --> 00:35:30,612
The first step to me,

827
00:35:30,612 --> 00:35:32,993
how I'd like to describe Naughty Dog's goals

828
00:35:32,993 --> 00:35:35,434
is to create a playable storyboard.

829
00:35:35,434 --> 00:35:38,235
Step one of this is actually breaking the story.

830
00:35:38,235 --> 00:35:42,576
We sit down with the writers, we read the pitch,

831
00:35:42,576 --> 00:35:44,836
we grab the lead into a meeting and we just talk about it.

832
00:35:44,836 --> 00:35:47,177
We figure out in a brainstorm,

833
00:35:48,533 --> 00:35:49,714
what we're trying to accomplish,

834
00:35:49,714 --> 00:35:51,055
what are interesting things that we can do,

835
00:35:51,055 --> 00:35:53,877
using all of these things that we've talked about before.

836
00:35:53,877 --> 00:35:56,960
We literally went to a seminar hosted by Robert McKee

837
00:35:56,960 --> 00:35:58,401
early when I started there,

838
00:35:58,401 --> 00:36:00,442
just to have a shared language

839
00:36:00,442 --> 00:36:02,324
that we could start chewing on this,

840
00:36:02,324 --> 00:36:03,945
start breaking this down into manageable parts

841
00:36:03,945 --> 00:36:05,746
and make it happen.

842
00:36:05,746 --> 00:36:08,929
After that meeting,

843
00:36:08,929 --> 00:36:12,131
level designer would break off with the lead

844
00:36:12,131 --> 00:36:14,613
and just plan a first pass.

845
00:36:14,613 --> 00:36:16,814
We would try to get all of this done

846
00:36:16,814 --> 00:36:18,035
in like less than two days.

847
00:36:18,384 --> 00:36:23,387
It's a very, very concise but focused start to all of this.

848
00:36:23,387 --> 00:36:25,889
The next step though is what I like to call

849
00:36:25,889 --> 00:36:27,470
3D first design.

850
00:36:27,470 --> 00:36:29,531
We would just jump straight into Maya.

851
00:36:29,531 --> 00:36:32,213
No top-down maps, maybe just a rough outline,

852
00:36:32,213 --> 00:36:36,375
maybe a few scribbles, nothing substantial

853
00:36:36,375 --> 00:36:38,176
beyond actually getting a mesh done

854
00:36:38,176 --> 00:36:39,037
that I can walk around in.

855
00:36:39,037 --> 00:36:40,938
We get the block mesh in engine

856
00:36:40,938 --> 00:36:42,959
and we try to actually move the character

857
00:36:42,959 --> 00:36:44,380
in the camera around to see if it starts working.

858
00:36:45,250 --> 00:36:47,371
The reason I think this is one of the best ways to do it

859
00:36:47,371 --> 00:36:48,831
is it's the fastest way to test an idea.

860
00:36:48,831 --> 00:36:51,692
You can see if this even makes sense,

861
00:36:51,692 --> 00:36:53,952
if this feels too big or too small,

862
00:36:53,952 --> 00:36:55,253
if the camera doesn't make any sense,

863
00:36:55,253 --> 00:36:57,113
if you can even accomplish something like

864
00:36:57,113 --> 00:36:59,294
revealing a dinosaur to somebody

865
00:36:59,294 --> 00:37:01,234
by wandering through a forest.

866
00:37:01,234 --> 00:37:02,574
You can say all of those things,

867
00:37:02,574 --> 00:37:04,815
but it doesn't matter unless you can prove

868
00:37:04,815 --> 00:37:06,675
that it actually works in engine.

869
00:37:06,675 --> 00:37:09,036
And it's also important to do it so fast

870
00:37:09,036 --> 00:37:11,316
because it lets you assume that things will be thrown away.

871
00:37:11,316 --> 00:37:14,197
Going back to that living process and that iteration.

872
00:37:15,035 --> 00:37:19,196
you were intentionally making this to die.

873
00:37:19,196 --> 00:37:21,416
Like, don't care about it,

874
00:37:21,416 --> 00:37:24,497
don't feel as little pain to shove it out and try again.

875
00:37:24,497 --> 00:37:27,398
But yeah, what also do we mean

876
00:37:27,398 --> 00:37:29,119
when we're talking about storyboards?

877
00:37:29,119 --> 00:37:31,219
What do we mean playable storyboard?

878
00:37:31,219 --> 00:37:35,440
So I think for extra context on what I was just saying,

879
00:37:35,440 --> 00:37:36,761
a lot of storyboards are like this.

880
00:37:36,761 --> 00:37:39,301
Like this is from Knives Out.

881
00:37:39,301 --> 00:37:42,762
The image on the right is their initial concept

882
00:37:42,762 --> 00:37:43,903
for this shot.

883
00:37:45,494 --> 00:37:46,775
Just soak it in.

884
00:37:46,775 --> 00:37:48,555
You don't need to be a master illustrator

885
00:37:48,555 --> 00:37:51,316
to convey your ideas.

886
00:37:51,316 --> 00:37:53,277
And now I'm gonna show you what we dealt with

887
00:37:53,277 --> 00:37:55,298
in the early stages of development.

