00:38:40,426 --> 00:38:43,987
This is what he normally draws like in a finished product,

907
00:38:43,987 --> 00:38:44,427
but again.

908
00:38:45,319 --> 00:38:46,860
He starts with this.

909
00:38:46,860 --> 00:38:49,241
Starts with something that can be thrown away

910
00:38:49,241 --> 00:38:50,062
just to see if the idea works.

911
00:38:50,062 --> 00:38:55,085
So yeah, once we have this thing,

912
00:38:55,085 --> 00:38:56,726
once we have this playable storyboard,

913
00:38:56,726 --> 00:38:58,667
we walk through the block mesh with the leads.

914
00:38:58,667 --> 00:39:03,690
We actually sit down face to face and just talk through it.

915
00:39:03,690 --> 00:39:05,611
We fill in the gaps of animation and art

916
00:39:05,611 --> 00:39:07,973
and dialogue with our performance.

917
00:39:07,973 --> 00:39:09,754
Like I mentioned, we were all ex-theater kids.

918
00:39:09,754 --> 00:39:10,234
Or not all, but.

919
00:39:12,106 --> 00:39:13,787
We all acted like we were ex-theater kids.

920
00:39:13,787 --> 00:39:16,348
We just lived in the scene with each other.

921
00:39:16,348 --> 00:39:17,408
We tried to figure it out.

922
00:39:17,408 --> 00:39:19,789
We would just wildly gesture and say,

923
00:39:19,789 --> 00:39:23,111
like, oh, it'll look like this, it'll be great, you know?

924
00:39:23,111 --> 00:39:25,252
And it led to a lot of great moments.

925
00:39:25,252 --> 00:39:28,233
The first time I showed this off to the leads,

926
00:39:28,233 --> 00:39:29,994
one of them, right out of their mouth,

927
00:39:29,994 --> 00:39:31,154
can I climb the dinosaur?

928
00:39:31,154 --> 00:39:35,836
Like, the grin on their face was phenomenal.

929
00:39:35,836 --> 00:39:38,317
When we said, yeah, sure, we could totally do that.

930
00:39:38,317 --> 00:39:38,778
And then we did.

931
00:39:38,778 --> 00:39:40,698
Same thing with the hats.

932
00:39:40,698 --> 00:39:41,939
It was just a dumb joke I made.

933
00:39:42,869 --> 00:39:46,850
just totally off the cuff and it wound up being a feature

934
00:39:46,850 --> 00:39:48,851
that a lot of people really like.

935
00:39:48,851 --> 00:39:52,952
So yeah, we would talk about what sucked and what worked.

936
00:39:52,952 --> 00:39:54,932
We would use all of that compositional stuff

937
00:39:54,932 --> 00:39:56,372
we covered in the first part of this talk

938
00:39:56,372 --> 00:39:59,373
to analyze what was good to move forward with

939
00:39:59,373 --> 00:40:01,494
and what we needed to cut or redo.

940
00:40:01,494 --> 00:40:05,455
And we just literally throw it all out again and redo.

941
00:40:05,455 --> 00:40:08,315
It's the power of iteration.

942
00:40:08,315 --> 00:40:09,316
You rework it until it clicks.

943
00:40:10,560 --> 00:40:12,901
Normally we would spend about several weeks iterating,

944
00:40:12,901 --> 00:40:15,162
like four to 12, depending on the complexity.

945
00:40:15,162 --> 00:40:18,063
That's total, mind you, not per iteration.

946
00:40:18,063 --> 00:40:20,824
Four to 12 weeks of figuring out this block mesh,

947
00:40:20,824 --> 00:40:22,705
this playable storyboard.

948
00:40:22,705 --> 00:40:26,386
Again, like including starting from scratch.

949
00:40:26,386 --> 00:40:28,567
Like we tried to keep this as limited

950
00:40:28,567 --> 00:40:30,087
and light as possible.

951
00:40:30,087 --> 00:40:31,588
This is the part where the level designer

952
00:40:31,588 --> 00:40:33,589
was the only person working on it.

953
00:40:33,589 --> 00:40:35,049
But yeah, it lets it grow and breathe

954
00:40:35,049 --> 00:40:35,910
as we get a feel for it.

955
00:40:35,910 --> 00:40:37,430
We don't really even know at this point.

956
00:40:37,840 --> 00:40:39,101
how long the final level is going to be.

957
00:40:39,101 --> 00:40:42,764
You could add a third, double it, cut it, shift it around,

958
00:40:42,764 --> 00:40:45,105
try radical different flows and beats of the elements.

959
00:40:45,105 --> 00:40:48,027
Like the dinosaur kind of came in early,

960
00:40:48,027 --> 00:40:51,729
but for example, the space capsule, that whole entire scene,

961
00:40:51,729 --> 00:40:53,891
that wasn't until like the last quarter

962
00:40:53,891 --> 00:40:56,032
of this like ideation process,

963
00:40:56,032 --> 00:40:58,273
before the graffiti was just gonna be right after

964
00:40:58,273 --> 00:41:01,055
the main part of the museum and on the space capsule itself.

965
00:41:01,055 --> 00:41:05,538
But in going through this process,

966
00:41:05,538 --> 00:41:07,279
me and the leads like wanted more.

967
00:41:07,697 --> 00:41:08,818
We figured out what to add,

968
00:41:08,818 --> 00:41:12,961
and then I just went back into Maya and added more.

969
00:41:12,961 --> 00:41:15,303
But yeah, once we have this rough sketch done,

970
00:41:15,303 --> 00:41:16,624
this playable storyboard, that's great,

971
00:41:16,624 --> 00:41:19,847
but that's not enough.

972
00:41:19,847 --> 00:41:24,271
The next stage is getting into alphas and playtesting.

973
00:41:24,271 --> 00:41:25,832
We try to build a playable prototype.

974
00:41:25,832 --> 00:41:27,474
That's where the first stage

975
00:41:27,474 --> 00:41:29,475
is we're taking it to other designers.

976
00:41:29,475 --> 00:41:32,598
We're trying to limit our gesturing, our manic energy,

977
00:41:33,307 --> 00:41:35,268
convey the story and just let it speak more

978
00:41:35,268 --> 00:41:36,969
and more for itself.

979
00:41:36,969 --> 00:41:39,630
That's when we also start adding in more developers.

980
00:41:39,630 --> 00:41:41,832
It's like I said, the four to six person strike team

981
00:41:41,832 --> 00:41:45,074
that supports the level designer to actually finish

982
00:41:45,074 --> 00:41:47,355
and develop features.

983
00:41:47,355 --> 00:41:49,056
And then work towards that first playable.

984
00:41:49,056 --> 00:41:54,680
First playable means the first time you can just shut up

985
00:41:54,680 --> 00:41:56,181
and let someone play it on their own.

986
00:41:56,181 --> 00:41:59,283
No guides, no role presentation.

987
00:41:59,283 --> 00:42:02,565
I hand it to you, I leave the room, does it work or not?

988
00:42:03,941 --> 00:42:05,382
Again, I would have some video for you,

989
00:42:05,382 --> 00:42:08,224
but unfortunately not, all on my website.

990
00:42:08,224 --> 00:42:10,486
And then once we hit that stage,

991
00:42:10,486 --> 00:42:13,768
once I can actually hand it to you and leave,

992
00:42:13,768 --> 00:42:17,711
we grab some outside people, hand it to them and leave.

993
00:42:17,711 --> 00:42:21,514
So every few weeks we would have outside people come in,

994
00:42:21,514 --> 00:42:23,076
they'd have really detailed feedback,

995
00:42:23,076 --> 00:42:26,178
and we do this about a cadence of every two to three weeks

996
00:42:26,178 --> 00:42:27,819
as we're shifting through production.

997
00:42:27,819 --> 00:42:30,842
So this would be a studio-wide event.

998
00:42:32,369 --> 00:42:34,851
And trust me, when you start play testing,

999
00:42:34,851 --> 00:42:37,253
thoroughly like this or not,

1000
00:42:37,253 --> 00:42:38,794
you will see how bad your layout really is.

1001
00:42:38,794 --> 00:42:41,816
Everything that was duct taped over

1002
00:42:41,816 --> 00:42:44,217
with good intentions and slick presentations

1003
00:42:44,217 --> 00:42:46,659
just falls away.

1004
00:42:46,659 --> 00:42:48,481
You will watch people get lost,

1005
00:42:48,481 --> 00:42:51,703
not care about your story, complain,

1006
00:42:51,703 --> 00:42:54,285
and worst of all, be right about all of it.

1007
00:42:54,285 --> 00:42:56,006
Just rip it apart.

1008
00:42:59,271 --> 00:43:01,472
Also because of this cycle, this like tempo

1009
00:43:01,472 --> 00:43:02,592
where every two to three weeks,

1010
00:43:02,592 --> 00:43:04,572
we knew we were gonna be bringing in new people.

1011
00:43:04,572 --> 00:43:07,073
We knew that, oh, I fucked up.

1012
00:43:07,073 --> 00:43:09,494
That level sucked.

1013
00:43:09,494 --> 00:43:12,815
What can I do in the next three weeks to make it better?

1014
00:43:12,815 --> 00:43:15,555
What can I do to ensure that I don't break this

1015
00:43:15,555 --> 00:43:18,036
and it's still playable in three weeks too?

1016
00:43:18,036 --> 00:43:23,078
Yeah, so all the changes need to be playable.

1017
00:43:23,078 --> 00:43:24,818
We had so much data to work with though.

1018
00:43:24,818 --> 00:43:26,298
It was massively helpful.

1019
00:43:26,902 --> 00:43:29,644
And another level with it too, it was studio-wide tempo.

1020
00:43:29,644 --> 00:43:31,005
It wasn't just playtesting your level,

1021
00:43:31,005 --> 00:43:32,947
it was playtesting all the levels at once.

1022
00:43:32,947 --> 00:43:34,609
Then we would go back to iteration,

1023
00:43:34,609 --> 00:43:36,871
and then playtest all the levels at once.

1024
00:43:36,871 --> 00:43:40,014
It really helped facilitate just a cohesion.

1025
00:43:40,014 --> 00:43:41,315
Everybody knew what was on the schedule.

1026
00:43:41,315 --> 00:43:42,896
Everybody knew what needed to get done.

1027
00:43:42,896 --> 00:43:44,958
We were able to focus on tighter milestones.

1028
00:43:47,570 --> 00:43:49,251
But from there, we would also take all of that data

1029
00:43:49,251 --> 00:43:50,132
and try to dial things in.

1030
00:43:50,132 --> 00:43:51,993
That's when the more formal reviews

1031
00:43:51,993 --> 00:43:54,655
with studio leadership would tend to happen.

1032
00:43:54,655 --> 00:43:55,936
We'd refine features and scripting

1033
00:43:55,936 --> 00:43:57,837
and prove out any ideas that we have

1034
00:43:57,837 --> 00:44:00,519
with playtest feedback rather than just wildly gesturing,

1035
00:44:00,519 --> 00:44:02,220
hey guys, I think this is a really good idea.

1036
00:44:02,220 --> 00:44:04,841
Instead, we can go like, hey, this part,

1037
00:44:04,841 --> 00:44:07,503
objectively people like it, they keep talking about it.

1038
00:44:07,503 --> 00:44:10,165
Let's improve this or fix this.

1039
00:44:10,165 --> 00:44:11,686
Again, it's just all about trying

1040
00:44:11,686 --> 00:44:13,587
to facilitate effective iteration.

