00:44:13,587 --> 00:44:14,107
But even at this stage,

1042
00:44:17,237 --> 00:44:19,938
You know, we tried to cut things early,

1043
00:44:19,938 --> 00:44:20,738
throw things out fast,

1044
00:44:20,738 --> 00:44:22,579
but there's still gonna be a lot of rework.

1045
00:44:22,579 --> 00:44:24,740
Cuts, revisions, additions.

1046
00:44:24,740 --> 00:44:26,360
We use the entire team for input at this point.

1047
00:44:26,360 --> 00:44:28,641
Starting from scratch is almost limited

1048
00:44:28,641 --> 00:44:31,683
to specific sections, but it's still fairly common.

1049
00:44:31,683 --> 00:44:32,663
We call it back to layout,

1050
00:44:32,663 --> 00:44:34,824
where a chunk of the level might just be kind of

1051
00:44:34,824 --> 00:44:36,845
sawed out and redone.

1052
00:44:36,845 --> 00:44:40,306
Honest example of this was that space section.

1053
00:44:40,306 --> 00:44:43,748
We were pretty confident in the rest of the layout

1054
00:44:43,748 --> 00:44:44,888
and the rest of the area, but.

1055
00:44:45,395 --> 00:44:46,816
There were a few times where we just looked

1056
00:44:46,816 --> 00:44:49,237
at that upper area, that second floor,

1057
00:44:49,237 --> 00:44:52,980
and we had art done for it, we had some features in,

1058
00:44:52,980 --> 00:44:55,562
and it just wasn't right.

1059
00:44:55,562 --> 00:44:59,965
And we kind of pulled the trigger on redoing it again.

1060
00:44:59,965 --> 00:45:02,066
And yeah, just going back to that iteration,

1061
00:45:02,066 --> 00:45:05,409
that living process, you just keep trying to make it work.

1062
00:45:05,409 --> 00:45:11,233
You keep redoing and redoing and redoing.

1063
00:45:11,233 --> 00:45:13,875
But what happens when it does work?

1064
00:45:15,047 --> 00:45:16,848
Like YouTube just burnt all of this effort,

1065
00:45:16,848 --> 00:45:19,010
like desperately trying to make this thing work.

1066
00:45:19,010 --> 00:45:20,231
And now it does.

1067
00:45:20,231 --> 00:45:21,792
And now what?

1068
00:45:21,792 --> 00:45:23,953
That's when you lock the layout.

1069
00:45:23,953 --> 00:45:27,035
The level is moved from prototype to alpha.

1070
00:45:27,035 --> 00:45:29,517
Now the rest of the team can be brought in

1071
00:45:29,517 --> 00:45:31,878
to actually make this thing shippable.

1072
00:45:31,878 --> 00:45:34,680
Which brings us to full production.

1073
00:45:35,885 --> 00:45:37,745
This is the part where everything gets ramped up.

1074
00:45:37,745 --> 00:45:40,066
We bring off, hand off to the other departments.

1075
00:45:40,066 --> 00:45:41,166
This isn't a comprehensive list,

1076
00:45:41,166 --> 00:45:43,407
but you know, an example is like audio, VFX,

1077
00:45:43,407 --> 00:45:46,128
mocap, dialogue, character art, AI, foreground,

1078
00:45:46,128 --> 00:45:48,569
technical art, environment art, animation,

1079
00:45:48,569 --> 00:45:50,930
cinematics, QA, and on and on and on and on.

1080
00:45:50,930 --> 00:45:52,810
This is when we take it from just,

1081
00:45:52,810 --> 00:45:54,231
oh, the designers are working on this cool thing

1082
00:45:54,231 --> 00:45:56,231
with a small group of people to everyone needs to know

1083
00:45:56,231 --> 00:45:57,692
about every detail all of the time.

1084
00:45:57,692 --> 00:46:00,533
It also really helps collaboration.

1085
00:46:01,234 --> 00:46:04,017
We then start really focusing on feedback and direction,

1086
00:46:04,017 --> 00:46:05,879
more as level designers, more than anything else.

1087
00:46:05,879 --> 00:46:07,741
This is when it goes hands off.

1088
00:46:07,741 --> 00:46:10,143
Like, I should not be in Maya,

1089
00:46:10,143 --> 00:46:11,645
I should not be in editor,

1090
00:46:11,645 --> 00:46:13,427
messing with things other than gameplay scripting.

1091
00:46:13,427 --> 00:46:16,010
So yeah, it's like I shift time

1092
00:46:16,010 --> 00:46:16,971
to other levels at this point.

1093
00:46:16,971 --> 00:46:18,993
Like maybe I start the whole process over

1094
00:46:18,993 --> 00:46:21,495
on another section, or start scripting gameplay

1095
00:46:21,495 --> 00:46:22,016
for the scene.

1096
00:46:24,187 --> 00:46:26,288
A big part of this, at least in the Naughty Dog process

1097
00:46:26,288 --> 00:46:27,169
and in making this up for me,

1098
00:46:27,169 --> 00:46:28,650
was coordinating the team as well.

1099
00:46:28,650 --> 00:46:31,531
I was the one scheduling meetings, relaying information,

1100
00:46:31,531 --> 00:46:32,692
managing task loads and deadlines,

1101
00:46:32,692 --> 00:46:36,554
and also facilitating the review process.

1102
00:46:36,554 --> 00:46:38,635
I really liked what we did on this project,

1103
00:46:38,635 --> 00:46:41,917
where we would have large recorded meetings,

1104
00:46:41,917 --> 00:46:44,519
where we would just play through the level

1105
00:46:44,519 --> 00:46:45,719
and note down every single thing that was wrong.

1106
00:46:45,719 --> 00:46:47,621
And this would be like maybe eight people at some times,

1107
00:46:47,621 --> 00:46:50,502
just pausing, commenting, pausing, commenting.

1108
00:46:50,502 --> 00:46:52,443
So a 20-minute level might be three hours

1109
00:46:52,443 --> 00:46:53,784
of commentary video.

1110
00:46:54,663 --> 00:46:56,444
But we also had this annotation software

1111
00:46:56,444 --> 00:47:00,565
where you could take the recording and just make a note,

1112
00:47:00,565 --> 00:47:02,446
turn that note into a Jira ticket,

1113
00:47:02,446 --> 00:47:03,406
hand it all to the level designer,

1114
00:47:03,406 --> 00:47:05,367
hand off all the Jira tickets to the people

1115
00:47:05,367 --> 00:47:08,568
that need to get it done.

1116
00:47:08,568 --> 00:47:11,949
But yeah, this is mostly focused, specific feedback.

1117
00:47:11,949 --> 00:47:13,970
Very rarely would this turn into a full rework,

1118
00:47:13,970 --> 00:47:16,310
a back to layout kick.

1119
00:47:16,310 --> 00:47:18,011
But yeah, how did I do this?

1120
00:47:18,011 --> 00:47:19,091
What kind of fancy tools were there?

1121
00:47:19,091 --> 00:47:20,892
Nothing really important.

1122
00:47:20,892 --> 00:47:23,653
Face-to-face communication, legal pads.

1123
00:47:24,188 --> 00:47:27,331
Skype for business, email, JIRA, no silly proprietary

1124
00:47:27,331 --> 00:47:31,514
scrim board or anything else, just actual paper,

1125
00:47:31,514 --> 00:47:35,116
a few tags, and it kind of looks something like this.

1126
00:47:35,116 --> 00:47:37,538
For clarity, this is not at all for anything Naughty Dog,

1127
00:47:37,538 --> 00:47:39,359
this is just some personal projects that I kind of work with

1128
00:47:39,359 --> 00:47:41,121
but no, I would just kind of run around the office

1129
00:47:41,121 --> 00:47:42,101
like it was an Aaron Sorkin movie,

1130
00:47:42,101 --> 00:47:44,623
just talking to each department about every single thing

1131
00:47:44,623 --> 00:47:46,064
on my giant list I'd need done for the day.

1132
00:47:46,064 --> 00:47:48,686
I would break it down into sections with tabs,

1133
00:47:48,686 --> 00:47:52,529
and yeah, it was facilitating iteration.

1134
00:47:54,559 --> 00:48:00,441
And then the hard part comes, which is lock and polish.

1135
00:48:00,441 --> 00:48:03,642
So before when we said we handed things off,

1136
00:48:03,642 --> 00:48:05,422
it was kind of a lie, there were still reworks,

1137
00:48:05,422 --> 00:48:09,683
but this was the hard point where we would shift into,

1138
00:48:09,683 --> 00:48:12,484
we have deadlines, we're getting this done,

1139
00:48:12,484 --> 00:48:15,605
no major changes, push it from this janky prototype mess

1140
00:48:15,605 --> 00:48:19,946
to this thing that is naughty dog quality.

1141
00:48:19,946 --> 00:48:23,427
So in this polish stage, everything matters.

1142
00:48:24,044 --> 00:48:25,665
The review and the playtesting cycle I mentioned before

1143
00:48:25,665 --> 00:48:28,326
is continuing through this entire process, this entire span.

1144
00:48:28,326 --> 00:48:31,728
And the notes are picking up.

1145
00:48:31,728 --> 00:48:33,229
They're getting more and more.

1146
00:48:33,229 --> 00:48:34,449
It turns into a flood.

1147
00:48:34,449 --> 00:48:37,271
Every single department has tiny tweaks and everything,

1148
00:48:37,271 --> 00:48:40,732
but through all of this, it starts to finally take shape

1149
00:48:40,732 --> 00:48:41,713
into something that's gonna ship.

1150
00:48:41,713 --> 00:48:42,974
And yeah, a lot of this time,

1151
00:48:42,974 --> 00:48:46,175
even though there's no layouts to be done,

1152
00:48:46,175 --> 00:48:48,816
us in the level design department are running around,

1153
00:48:48,816 --> 00:48:50,857
doing additional scripting, fixing things.

1154
00:48:51,989 --> 00:48:53,670
We're just responsible to get things done.

1155
00:48:53,670 --> 00:48:56,252
I was basically a messenger boy on some days,

1156
00:48:56,252 --> 00:48:57,933
and it was hectic as heck,

1157
00:48:57,933 --> 00:49:00,974
because that's the real takeaway on this part of production.

1158
00:49:00,974 --> 00:49:01,895
The team does it.

1159
00:49:01,895 --> 00:49:04,997
All of these other developers that I worked with

1160
00:49:04,997 --> 00:49:06,658
are some of the most talented people

1161
00:49:06,658 --> 00:49:08,879
I probably will ever have the privilege to work with,

1162
00:49:08,879 --> 00:49:10,740
and they're just great.

1163
00:49:10,740 --> 00:49:13,782
They were on top of everything to the point that,

1164
00:49:13,782 --> 00:49:16,924
yeah, I was relegated to just running around,

1165
00:49:16,924 --> 00:49:17,985
conveying information in notes,

1166
00:49:17,985 --> 00:49:20,907
because, yeah, this.

1167
00:49:21,419 --> 00:49:24,141
that type of work isn't focused on somebody like me

1168
00:49:24,141 --> 00:49:25,321
or the leads.

1169
00:49:25,321 --> 00:49:30,464
It does take an entire massive organization to deliver.

1170
00:49:30,464 --> 00:49:33,986
And the result is honestly still just one of the things

1171
00:49:33,986 --> 00:49:35,687
I'm most proud to have helped on.

1172
00:49:35,687 --> 00:49:38,829
Like I, yeah, this was a joy to work on

1173
00:49:38,829 --> 00:49:43,792
and thanks for letting me do this talk.

1174
00:49:43,792 --> 00:49:44,752
So yeah, that's it.

1175
00:49:44,752 --> 00:49:46,513
We've covered composition and production,

1176
00:49:46,513 --> 00:49:48,675
hopefully giving you a bit of an insight into.

1177
00:49:49,280 --> 00:49:50,900
what it takes to make a Naughty Dog level,

1178
00:49:50,900 --> 00:49:53,261
specifically a weird one like this.

1179
00:49:53,261 --> 00:49:55,821
But yeah, final housekeeping,

1180
00:49:55,821 --> 00:49:57,061
let's cover some of the takeaways.

1181
00:49:57,061 --> 00:49:59,742
You wanna find a useful framework.

1182
00:49:59,742 --> 00:50:00,762
For us, it was story.

1183
00:50:00,762 --> 00:50:01,863
For you, it can be something else,

1184
00:50:01,863 --> 00:50:05,823
competitive integrity, counterplay, whatever it is,

1185
00:50:05,823 --> 00:50:07,264
you use them to guide iteration.

1186
00:50:07,264 --> 00:50:09,904
Start it rough as fast as you can, you fail,

1187
00:50:09,904 --> 00:50:15,086
you pick yourself up, often by finding some inspiration,

1188
00:50:15,086 --> 00:50:17,946
you iterate more, fail more,

1189
00:50:17,946 --> 00:50:19,247
try not to stop until it's great.

1190
00:50:20,195 --> 00:50:21,035
and you rely on your team.

1191
00:50:21,035 --> 00:50:24,236
That's it.

1192
00:50:24,236 --> 00:50:27,897
Hope you guys can follow me.

1193
00:50:27,897 --> 00:50:29,057
This is my Twitter.

1194
00:50:29,057 --> 00:50:32,478
I'm gonna be working on some secret podcast stuff

1195
00:50:32,478 --> 00:50:33,419
that'll hopefully come out soon.

1196
00:50:33,419 --> 00:50:35,679
And then the main thing is,

1197
00:50:35,679 --> 00:50:36,880
I'll be contributing to Outer Worlds 2.

1198
00:50:36,880 --> 00:50:39,641
And here's a list of resources.

1199
00:50:39,641 --> 00:50:40,941
Also go watch Liz and the Bluebird,

1200
00:50:40,941 --> 00:50:42,662
and A Silent Voice, and The Hickey Story.

1201
00:50:42,662 --> 00:50:44,502
I'm not kidding, they're really, really good.

1202
00:50:44,502 --> 00:50:46,383
And we have time for questions.

1203
00:51:01,747 --> 00:51:03,269
Hi, great talk.

1204
00:51:03,269 --> 00:51:06,133
Question about the playtesting every two, three weeks

1205
00:51:06,133 --> 00:51:10,318
that you mentioned, especially early on in the process.

1206
00:51:10,318 --> 00:51:11,880
What does that look like in terms of the questions

1207
00:51:11,880 --> 00:51:13,342
that you're asking the playtesters?

1208
00:51:13,342 --> 00:51:15,344
Is it very directed to a specific thing

1209
00:51:15,344 --> 00:51:17,487
that you're trying to accomplish?

1210
00:51:17,487 --> 00:51:18,168
Do you start out general?

1211
00:51:18,548 --> 00:51:19,029
How does that work?

1212
00:51:19,029 --> 00:51:20,490
I can't get too, too specific

1213
00:51:20,490 --> 00:51:22,572
because Sony really has been refining

1214
00:51:22,572 --> 00:51:24,473
their process constantly.

1215
00:51:24,473 --> 00:51:27,696
But in general, it's a lot of data,

1216
00:51:27,696 --> 00:51:32,039
big questionnaires, group feedbacks, focus tests.

1217
00:51:32,039 --> 00:51:33,320
So yeah, just literally anything

1218
00:51:33,320 --> 00:51:34,541
that we thought would help, we would throw at it.

1219
00:51:34,541 --> 00:51:37,043
There wasn't like a framework that we really worked from.

1220
00:51:37,043 --> 00:51:38,764
We're just like, what would we like to know

1221
00:51:38,764 --> 00:51:40,826
and what would they like to tell us?

1222
00:51:43,209 --> 00:51:44,070
Hi, thanks for the talk.

1223
00:51:44,070 --> 00:51:48,273
I was kind of on the same page as him,

1224
00:51:48,273 --> 00:51:50,755
asking about feedback from outside players.

1225
00:51:50,755 --> 00:51:51,856
How do you kind of handle that?

1226
00:51:51,856 --> 00:51:54,958
And how do you know what's good feedback

1227
00:51:54,958 --> 00:51:56,259
versus bad feedback?

1228
00:51:56,259 --> 00:51:58,801
I mean, you're the level designer, you know best.

1229
00:51:58,801 --> 00:52:00,022
How do you know what to listen to?

1230
00:52:00,022 --> 00:52:01,583
No, that's a really great question.

1231
00:52:01,583 --> 00:52:03,385
So in case it wasn't picked up,

1232
00:52:03,385 --> 00:52:04,766
how do you know it's good feedback?

1233
00:52:04,766 --> 00:52:05,806
How do you know it's bad feedback?

1234
00:52:05,806 --> 00:52:07,167
How do you turn them into notes?

1235
00:52:07,167 --> 00:52:09,709
A good rule of thumb I've always liked

1236
00:52:09,709 --> 00:52:11,631
is that the player is.

1237
00:52:12,477 --> 00:52:15,018
usually right that something is wrong,

1238
00:52:15,018 --> 00:52:16,639
but usually wrong about what specifically

1239
00:52:16,639 --> 00:52:17,639
is causing the problem.

1240
00:52:17,639 --> 00:52:22,042
The classic example was there was a first person shooter

1241
00:52:22,042 --> 00:52:24,683
where the two sides had identically,

1242
00:52:24,683 --> 00:52:26,004
statistically damaging guns.

1243
00:52:26,004 --> 00:52:27,845
Same fire rate, everything else like that.

1244
00:52:27,845 --> 00:52:30,927
But the sound effects on one

1245
00:52:30,927 --> 00:52:33,688
sounded more aggressive and more intense than the other.

1246
00:52:33,688 --> 00:52:35,469
And as a result, the players kept giving feedback,

1247
00:52:35,469 --> 00:52:37,190
like oh, this gun's more powerful than this one,

1248
00:52:37,190 --> 00:52:38,431
this gun's more powerful than this one,

1249
00:52:38,431 --> 00:52:39,972
you need to nerf this.

1250
00:52:39,972 --> 00:52:42,113
You're able to analyze that it's statistically identical.

1251
00:52:43,261 --> 00:52:45,042
The only difference was actually the sound effect.

1252
00:52:45,042 --> 00:52:48,083
They boosted the gain on it, the note went away.

1253
00:52:48,083 --> 00:52:50,023
Again, players are telling you something's wrong

1254
00:52:50,023 --> 00:52:51,304
because there's usually something wrong.

1255
00:52:51,304 --> 00:52:53,805
But they will always, the other thing to understand

1256
00:52:53,805 --> 00:52:56,726
is they'll always reach to the most obvious answer,

1257
00:52:56,726 --> 00:52:58,066
the most proximate answer,

1258
00:52:58,066 --> 00:52:59,587
the thing that's the most in their perception

1259
00:52:59,587 --> 00:53:01,527
because they feel it, they see it,

1260
00:53:01,527 --> 00:53:02,948
they give you the feedback, but yeah.

1261
00:53:05,595 --> 00:53:07,356
One more playtesting question.

1262
00:53:07,356 --> 00:53:10,298
How much do you have the same group of humans come in

1263
00:53:10,298 --> 00:53:12,740
to see if your new iteration works differently

1264
00:53:12,740 --> 00:53:14,481
versus try to vary them to make sure

1265
00:53:14,481 --> 00:53:17,723
that you're not just designing for that group of people?

1266
00:53:17,723 --> 00:53:20,645
Oh, we would try to get fresh feedback as much as possible.

1267
00:53:20,645 --> 00:53:23,047
Very rarely, I've forgotten if we ever brought

1268
00:53:23,047 --> 00:53:25,608
entire groups back or entire individuals back,

1269
00:53:25,608 --> 00:53:27,129
but in general with outside playtesting,

1270
00:53:27,129 --> 00:53:30,212
the idea is fresh first player experience.

1271
00:53:30,212 --> 00:53:31,112
And then that kind of,

1272
00:53:31,387 --> 00:53:34,029
Longitudinal iteration would just be mostly design team,

1273
00:53:34,029 --> 00:53:36,712
the people who are also the other developers.

1274
00:53:36,712 --> 00:53:39,834
The people who are making the game would kind of provide

1275
00:53:39,834 --> 00:53:41,896
that like, oh, where were we six months ago

1276
00:53:41,896 --> 00:53:43,637
and where are we now type analysis.

1277
00:53:43,637 --> 00:53:45,459
Thank you.

1278
00:53:45,459 --> 00:53:47,000
Quick question about the, I guess,

1279
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:49,302
the proportion of time that you spent on the blockouts

1280
00:53:49,302 --> 00:53:50,863
versus the polish stage.

1281
00:53:50,863 --> 00:53:51,784
What was that like?

1282
00:53:52,579 --> 00:53:53,760
It was pretty variable.

1283
00:53:53,760 --> 00:53:55,340
I can't give you a hard time on it

1284
00:53:55,340 --> 00:53:57,941
because it was all just very fluid, very focused,

1285
00:53:57,941 --> 00:53:59,782
and the directors were the ones

1286
00:53:59,782 --> 00:54:02,363
kind of setting the final deadlines.

1287
00:54:02,363 --> 00:54:06,905
But again, I would wanna say an eighth of the time

1288
00:54:06,905 --> 00:54:09,987
or less was that initial ideation process,

1289
00:54:09,987 --> 00:54:13,188
and then it was probably somewhat close

1290
00:54:13,188 --> 00:54:16,430
to a quarter, a quarter, and then two quarters on polish.

1291
00:54:16,430 --> 00:54:19,331
That final stage of taking it from beta to.

1292
00:54:19,994 --> 00:54:23,495
ship, Naughty Dog is a bit longer than most other studios.

1293
00:54:23,495 --> 00:54:26,657
